u have freckles, but more importantly, your personality, you're\n\n33:45.360 --> 33:48.920\nsloppy, you're neat, you're...\n\n33:48.920 --> 33:53.800\nYou're practicing being exceptional, and everyone else is practicing being everyone\n\n33:53.800 --> 33:55.720\nelse.\n\n33:55.720 --> 34:05.200\nAnd you go into your adulthood with these traumatic labels about the things that people\n\n34:05.200 --> 34:08.480\npointed out about you as you were developing.\n\n34:08.480 --> 34:15.560\nBecause whatever made you different than everyone else, absolutely this is not...\n\n34:15.560 --> 34:21.560\nSociety's job is to try to call you out and go, you're sloppier than everyone else.\n\n34:21.560 --> 34:27.280\nYou're fatter, you're taller, you're weirder, you're slower, you're faster.\n\n34:27.280 --> 34:32.080\nBut when you're a kid and you're developing, you're like, okay, I need to fix that shit,\n\n34:32.080 --> 34:34.600\nor I'm in big trouble.\n\n34:34.600 --> 34:39.240\nAnd it's right of you to want to fit in.\n\n34:39.240 --> 34:45.000\nBut then once you hit 18, 19, 20, it's time for you to drop that shit, actually.\n\n34:45.000 --> 34:49.880\nYour body's designed to drop that shit, but society's not designed to tell you when it's\n\n34:49.880 --> 34:54.440\ntime to let that go, because Sears and McDonald's are more than happy to step in and go, hey,\n\n34:54.440 --> 34:57.200\nyou don't want to be fucking weird, buy a Happy Meal, like no one's going to tell you\n\n34:57.200 --> 34:58.920\nto drop that shit.\n\n34:58.920 --> 35:03.880\nSam's class was telling you, okay, time to drop that shit.\n\n35:03.880 --> 35:06.960\nWhat sparks your shame?\n\n35:06.960 --> 35:12.320\nGo through his exercises, go through all your love letters from high school, go through\n\n35:12.320 --> 35:15.200\nyour yearbook signings.\n\n35:15.200 --> 35:20.320\nWe've been getting called the same names since we were children into our adulthood.\n\n35:20.320 --> 35:25.920\nAnd if somebody likes you, and let's say Dan, for instance, there's a way to describe how\n\n35:25.920 --> 35:27.400\nDan is smart.\n\n35:27.400 --> 35:33.880\nIf you like Dan, you say, oh, he's a genius, he's an intellect, he's a mastermind.\n\n35:33.880 --> 35:39.880\nIf you don't like Dan, you go, oh, he's a genius, and I hate him.\n\n35:39.880 --> 35:48.120\nBut being able to say in a couple words exactly how you're smart, Cody, and Bob, like what\n\n35:48.120 --> 35:57.200\nmakes you edgy, or what makes you the neighborhood of how we would describe you as being witty,\n\n35:57.200 --> 35:59.800\nbut precisely say it.\n\n35:59.800 --> 36:03.440\nAnd there's these words that we have all been called our whole lives.\n\n36:03.440 --> 36:07.640\nLike Sam pointed out early on when I first met him, and he said, Catherine Hepburn when\n\n36:07.640 --> 36:14.400\nshe was 18, or 19 when she did Philadelphia's story, every review called her feisty.\n\n36:14.400 --> 36:20.040\nWhen she was 80 something and she did Angold and Pond, everybody called her crusty.\n\n36:20.040 --> 36:26.720\nIf you're feisty at 18 and crusty at 80, what the essence is, is defiant.\n\n36:26.720 --> 36:30.320\nIsn't that like, you don't need men.\n\n36:30.320 --> 36:37.600\nAnd that's what made her great, was that all of her roles was, I don't need you.\n\n36:37.600 --> 36:40.920\nAnd if you're 18 or 80, it's a defiance.\n\n36:40.920 --> 36:44.160\nWe have different ways of saying what's special about you.\n\n36:44.160 --> 36:48.520\nTheir memories of what's said that's special about you on the playground are probably negative.\n\n36:48.520 --> 36:50.600\nThen you have lovers throughout your life.\n\n36:50.600 --> 36:52.920\nThey find the positive ways of saying it.\n\n36:52.920 --> 36:59.360\nIt doesn't really matter, and also crucially, it doesn't matter whether they're accurate.\n\n36:59.360 --> 37:06.240\nSam always used the example of Goldie Hawn, who is a very, very smart actor.\n\n37:06.240 --> 37:08.080\nShe could debate your ass off on any topic.\n\n37:08.080 --> 37:09.640\nShe happens to be intellectual.\n\n37:09.640 --> 37:15.920\nWhen she was young, it was her, the way the public wanted to perceive her, the way that\n\n37:15.920 --> 37:22.920\nshe would get gigs, it was like, people looked at her and said, you're an airhead, you're\n\n37:22.920 --> 37:31.040\na bimbo, you're a blonde, idiot, whatever, there's probably healthier ways to say that,\n\n37:31.040 --> 37:37.480\nbut that are equally not acknowledging the truth about her intellect or her depth.\n\n37:37.480 --> 37:42.960\nBut if you're presenting yourself to the public and you're for public consumption, it's not\n\n37:42.960 --> 37:47.440\nnecessarily a bad thing if people don't know everything about you.\n\n37:47.440 --> 37:52.040\nRight, because it's not the way you see you, but the way the world sees you.\n\n37:52.040 --> 37:53.040\nAnd that's what you have to discover.\n\n37:53.040 --> 37:55.920\nAnd that's what you have to step on that gas pedal and go, I always use the example of\n\n37:55.920 --> 38:02.840\nLouis Anderson, who would start his stand-up act, and he would do five or six fat jokes,\n\n38:02.840 --> 38:06.520\nand then he would pause and he'd wait, and the laughter subsided, and he goes, I start\n\n38:06.520 --> 38:11.760\nmy set with a bunch of fat jokes, because I know, it's like, oh, it's so predictable,\n\n38:11.760 --> 38:15.920\nbut also if I don't start my set that way, you guys are going to be out there for 45\n\n38:15.920 --> 38:20.000\nminutes, and some of you are going to be like, do you think he knows?\n\n38:20.000 --> 38:23.960\nAnd I always equated that with Sam's thing, where I was like, Charisma is Christopher\n\n38:23.960 --> 38:30.920\nWalken knowing he's creepy, Charisma is Jack Nicholson knowing he's dirty, Charisma is\n\n38:30.920 --> 38:37.280\na fat person leaning into the, they're like, well, I'm not going to try to convince you\n\n38:37.280 --> 38:38.280\nI'm not fat.\n\n38:38.280 --> 38:44.160\nThat has nothing to do with me endorsing body shaming or thinking it's better to be thin\n\n38:44.160 --> 38:45.160\nor whatever.\n\n38:45.160 --> 38:52.680\nIt's just like, there's a weird energy you exude the day you go, well, I'm kind of on\n\n38:52.680 --> 39:00.800\nthe same page with how I am perceived at first glance, and it kind of blows your mind, it's\n\n39:00.800 --> 39:08.320\nactually more likely that you're way off because of the amount of refraction, and I just remember\n\n39:08.320 --> 39:09.320\nthe exercises that we did.\n\n39:09.320 --> 39:13.320\nCan you tell us about the airport thing, because that was the one that was really interesting?\n\n39:13.320 --> 39:15.920\nYeah, I've said it on the show before too, it's like, just a rush through it, but it\n\n39:15.920 --> 39:19.680\nwas like, that was my big eye opener, where I was like, okay, this guy's not full of shit.\n\n39:19.680 --> 39:23.720\nWe went to the airport, it was pre-911, so you could just walk around the airport.\n\n39:23.720 --> 39:28.640\nAnd we would do this exercise, where we handed out forms and...\n\n39:28.640 --> 39:33.640\nYeah, it sounded like the worst idea, like, oh, this sounds like a horrible homework assignment,\n\n39:33.640 --> 39:35.640\nto go to the airport with somebody else in my class.\n\n39:35.640 --> 39:39.040\nSo people all around the international terminal are handed these forms and they go, so your\n\n39:39.040 --> 39:43.480\nclassmates say, look at that guy, so that guy's me, I don't say a word, I'm just leaning\n\n39:43.480 --> 39:44.480\ninto the pillar.\n\n39:44.480 --> 39:46.680\nYeah, like standing 100 feet away over by a pillar and you go like that.\n\n39:46.680 --> 39:50.200\nAnd you have this sheet in front of you with 300 words on it, and they don't give you a\n\n39:50.200 --> 39:54.640\nlimit, they don't ask you to engage like doing it right or wrong, and just circle any word\n\n39:54.640 --> 39:57.240\nthat you think applies to that guy over there, right there.\n\n39:57.240 --> 40:00.920\nHe's down with it, it's fine, you can stare at him, we're part of a psychology class,\n\n40:00.920 --> 40:02.680\nwe would say.\n\n40:02.680 --> 40:06.840\nAnd so they'd sit there, circle, people from Poland, people from Memphis, people from Fort\n\n40:06.840 --> 40:10.200\nLauderdale, like you're just in this LAX terminal.\n\n40:10.200 --> 40:15.320\nYou do that for five hours, you leave LAX with a giant stack of papers, you go home,\n\n40:15.320 --> 40:21.000\nyou tabulate everything, and then I'm like, why the fuck does everyone in the world think\n\n40:21.000 --> 40:22.000\nI'm sarcastic?\n\n40:22.000 --> 40:23.000\nAnd lazy.\n\n40:23.000 --> 40:30.000\nAnd you're just standing there, I went with a guy that looked like Charles Bronson, he\n\n40:30.000 --> 40:36.760\nwas a weird dude, and we got in the car and we did like 50 of them, and he's going through\n\n40:36.760 --> 40:47.880\nme, he's looking from side to side, he's like, what the fuck, what, god damn it, what does\n\n40:47.880 --> 40:48.880\neverybody think I'm suspicious?\n\n40:48.880 --> 40:52.640\nAnd Schrab went into the weekend class with Schrab, you're not supposed to look at your\n\n40:52.640 --> 40:56.520\ncards when you go to lunch, by the way, you were told.\n\n40:56.520 --> 40:57.520\nWhat?\n\n40:57.520 --> 40:58.520\nWhat is it?\n\n40:58.520 --> 41:04.520\nSo Schrab looked at his cards, apparently, because we did the same class, we were there\n\n41:04.520 --> 41:05.520\nfor hours.\n\n41:05.520 --> 41:10.760\nSo this is classmates writing down things about you, you take the class and your other\n\n41:10.760 --> 41:15.040\nclassmates write shit down as you get this exercise, okay, go to lunch, that was my\n\n41:15.040 --> 41:21.560\nimpression of Sam, and Schrab and I were walking down the sidewalk, and Schrab's like, and I'm\n\n41:21.560 --> 41:27.160\nlike, what's wrong, he's like, nothing, what did you get on your cards, and I didn't look\n\n41:27.160 --> 41:32.000\nat my cards, you're not supposed to look at your cards, and Schrab's like, and I'm like,\n\n41:32.000 --> 41:35.480\nokay, obviously you looked at your cards, what's your problem, and Rob goes, I am\n\n41:35.480 --> 41:36.480\nnot C-3PO.\n\n41:36.480 --> 41:51.800\nWaving his hands around with his elbows locked at 90 degrees, as if, as if, first of all,\n\n41:51.800 --> 41:58.480\nfirst of all, if I did that, I would be nothing like C-3PO, because he never did that.\n\n41:58.480 --> 42:03.280\nAnthony Daniels fucking, no, no, you're, you're embellishing to, to, okay, well, that's how\n\n42:03.280 --> 42:06.800\nI remember it, because you're Coney C-3PO.\n\n42:06.800 --> 42:13.280\nSam, part of the class, which is amazing, is like, he gives you, you kind of find out\n\n42:13.280 --> 42:18.000\nmythologically who you are, and like what your myth is, like where you live on Mount\n\n42:18.000 --> 42:22.560\nOlympus, and what the story is that you tell, because all of our favorite like actor and\n\n42:22.560 --> 42:26.960\nactresses, they all kind of portray the same role in different ways, but they're always\n\n42:26.960 --> 42:33.320\nkind of fulfilling a same kind of myth, and I asked Sam, was it, what's your myth?\n\n42:33.320 --> 42:39.160\nAnd he said, mine is to remove fear, and, and if, you could say anything great about\n\n42:39.160 --> 42:44.520\nSam, and there's lots of great things to say, Sam took fear away from people, and he gave\n\n42:44.520 --> 42:46.360\nyou like freedom.\n\n42:46.360 --> 42:50.240\nHe created this environment where I was, I was in my 20s, I was the worst version of\n\n42:50.240 --> 42:54.080\nme, and that's me talking, I'm already not a good person.\n\n42:54.080 --> 42:58.880\nEven me at 25, like where I'm like still cutting my teeth, being a human being, and\n\n42:58.880 --> 43:00.840\nit's like, but there was this space.\n\n43:00.840 --> 43:04.720\nAnyways, I think what we wanted to do is like, like we could have, we could have at any point\n\n43:04.720 --> 43:09.520\ntalked about, oh, these are Sam's superpowers, this is why you should be interested in them.\n\n43:09.520 --> 43:15.480\nI think Bob, your contribution to it is, you were, you were very close to him for, for\n\n43:15.480 --> 43:20.680\nhis whole life, and I, I, I asked you backstage, it kind of caught me off guard, it was like,\n\n43:20.680 --> 43:25.360\nwhen's the last time you saw him, because we saw him relatively recently, but you saw\n\n43:25.360 --> 43:27.800\nhim two weeks ago.\n\n43:27.800 --> 43:31.920\nWell, he'd come to my house every Friday night and we'd watch Bill Maher and we'd cook,\n\n43:31.920 --> 43:34.320\nand one of the things, talk about taking away fear.\n\n43:34.320 --> 43:35.320\nYeah.\n\n43:35.320 --> 43:37.120\nYou know, I just got a soup maker, right?\n\n43:37.120 --> 43:42.200\nSo I said, I'm going to make soup for you, and my new soup maker, which takes 18 minutes.\n\n43:42.200 --> 43:48.280\nSo I make this soup, and he said, he tastes it, and he says, yeah, yeah.\n\n43:48.280 --> 43:54.600\nAnd I said, what do you mean, yeah, he said, it's, it's good, but what would make it great\n\n43:54.600 --> 43:58.120\nis if you added an entire lemon to the soup.\n\n43:58.120 --> 44:01.800\nSo I squeezed the lemon into the soup, and he said, this is the best soup I've ever\n\n44:01.800 --> 44:02.800\nhad.\n\n44:02.800 --> 44:06.000\nWell, he's kind of, he's, he's pulling a little trick there.\n\n44:06.000 --> 44:10.000\nHe's, he's like, I think I'll create a story where I knew exactly what needed to be in\n\n44:10.000 --> 44:11.000\nthe soup.\n\n44:11.000 --> 44:12.000\nExactly.\n\n44:12.000 --> 44:13.000\nAnd then he's like, it was great.\n\n44:13.000 --> 44:16.240\nWhen you did Sam's class, the first part, back, when I did it back in the old days,\n\n44:16.240 --> 44:20.800\nlike, and like when you still could go to the airport and do that thing, later it became\n\n44:20.800 --> 44:25.880\nmore like online and internet based and faster.\n\n44:25.880 --> 44:28.720\nYou would do the class, you would get your essences, and then if you wanted to keep going,\n\n44:28.720 --> 44:33.400\nyou would do an acting class where you, you get a placard and you would put on a music\n\n44:33.400 --> 44:37.080\nstand with your seven statements about who you were.\n\n44:37.080 --> 44:41.560\nAnd it's the kind of the neighborhoods of, like, all the things people know about you\n\n44:41.560 --> 44:45.560\non site, but you don't know that people know that, and it was just getting used to admitting\n\n44:45.560 --> 44:48.500\nthat and knowing that people saw that stuff.\n\n44:48.500 --> 44:51.120\nAnd then you would do a monologue.\n\n44:51.120 --> 44:52.120\nSo you could be anything.\n\n44:52.120 --> 44:55.640\nIt could be a, I, I, I did something from network or you could do something from Shakespeare\n\n44:55.640 --> 44:57.720\nor whatever the, whatever the hell.\n\n44:57.720 --> 45:04.960\nAnd there was a guy in the class, it was a black guy, a really good actor, and he did\n\n45:04.960 --> 45:08.800\nthis piece where it was like a really angry piece, I forget what it was.\n\n45:08.800 --> 45:12.300\nAnd he had a ball cap on and Sam goes, let's do it again.\n\n45:12.300 --> 45:19.480\nI want you to turn your hat a little bit to the side, and instantly the guy looked furious.\n\n45:19.480 --> 45:22.960\nAnd he goes, just do it again, and turn your ball cap to the side.\n\n45:22.960 --> 45:25.760\nAnd he did it, and it was the fucking best acting you've ever saw.\n\n45:25.760 --> 45:29.880\nAnd when it was over, he instantly put his hat back straight, and Sam goes, why does\n\n45:29.880 --> 45:30.880\nthat make you so angry?\n\n45:30.880 --> 45:34.240\nHe goes, I don't want to be thought of as the guy that has the ball cap to the side.\n\n45:34.240 --> 45:38.440\nHe goes, you see how close your anger is?\n\n45:38.440 --> 45:44.000\nLike if you need it, all you have to do is be thought of or perceived as less than you\n\n45:44.000 --> 45:45.000\nare.\n\n45:45.000 --> 45:48.880\nRight, well that's the thing is like if people think that you, if you find out what your\n\n45:48.880 --> 45:53.920\nessence is, that's equally empowering if you want to play the opposite of it or whatever,\n\n45:53.920 --> 45:56.360\nlike being able to tap into your stuff.\n\n45:56.360 --> 46:01.280\nOne thing I'm curious about Bob now that he's gone, like you knowing Sam probably better\n\n46:01.280 --> 46:08.320\nthan, than, than us on stage, like, how did Sam like, did Sam have, did Sam have, did\n\n46:08.320 --> 46:15.080\nlike, where, where was he at, he was, he was this kind of guru, he had this studio in Burbank.\n\n46:15.080 --> 46:19.640\nMy perception of him was always that he, he had plans to make it bigger.\n\n46:19.640 --> 46:23.520\nHe would do the internet version, and he was like, he was trying to, he was trying to empire\n\n46:23.520 --> 46:29.160\nbuild, which I totally relate to, which I have tried to do, like, oh, I'm not enough\n\n46:29.160 --> 46:31.280\nthat I'm just going to do what I do.\n\n46:31.280 --> 46:37.440\nWas Sam, was he frustrated about the business of being Sam, or was he content with it?\n\n46:37.440 --> 46:38.760\nNo, he was content.\n\n46:38.760 --> 46:44.000\nFirst of all, he did a lot of traveling from, to New York and Atlanta and all over the country,\n\n46:44.000 --> 46:46.400\nand he'd go for weeks at a time.\n\n46:46.400 --> 46:51.280\nAnd that was very rewarding to him, because he blossomed this business to reach so many\n\n46:51.280 --> 46:57.920\npeople, but it was a business of really having people center in on who they really are and\n\n46:57.920 --> 47:03.520\nhow to maneuver them, their, their, themselves through life in a successful way.\n\n47:03.520 --> 47:06.080\nAnd that was incredibly rewarding to him.\n\n47:06.080 --> 47:12.080\nIt just seems like such a, that's good, I'